`IFormFile` buffers the entire request into memory by default. For large files, read the raw body stream directly and write to disk in chunks:

```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable the default form body size limit
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            && disposition.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var filePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", disposition.FileName.Value!);
            await using var stream = File.Create(filePath);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream); // streams in chunks, ~80KB default
        }
        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Key configuration (Program.cs or endpoint):**

```csharp
// Remove the 28MB default form size limit
builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(opt =>
{
    opt.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

// If using Kestrel, also raise the max request body size
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(k =>
{
    k.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

**Why this works:**

| Approach | Memory usage |
|----------|-------------|
| `IFormFile` | Buffers entire file (~2 GB in RAM) |
| `MultipartReader` | Streams in small chunks (~80 KB) |

**Additional tips:**

- Use `[RequestSizeLimit(2_147_483_648)]` on controllers if not using minimal APIs.
- If behind IIS, set `maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config`.
- If behind Nginx, set `client_max_body_size 2G;`.
- Consider writing to a temp file first, then renaming — protects against partial uploads.
